<h1>A closer look at the Electoral College</h1>

<p>
  With the general election heating up I thought it would be a good moment to take an analytical view of the electoral college.
</p>

<p>
  For those unaware, the electoral college is the actual system in which we elect a president. Every state has a number of electors assigned to it which is equal to your state's total house representatives plus two senators.
</p>

<p>
  These electors are the people who technically elect our president. It's not a free for all though, they are are legally bound to voting for one of the candidates based on the votes you cast in your state. So if 60% of the voters in my home state of NY vote for Clinton this fall, she gets the 31 electoral votes.
</p>

<p>
  The electoral college process dates back to the birth of the republic, and the founding fathers had two reasons for its creation. The first one was more of a fear from James Madison, worried that after George Washington served his time as president the people might elect a tyrant. Electors would ideally help be a buffer to make sure that never happened.
</p>

<p>
  The second reason it was created is to help equal out the voting power of the political majority & minority states. Back then, this was to prevent the south from forever being the minority. However in modern day, one of the popular phrases you might hear someone mention is that Wyoming has 4x the voting power of someone in NY, and this is technically true.
</p>

<p>
  In Wyoming, each of the 3 electoral votes is decided by about 190K voters. In contrast, each of NY’s 33 electoral votes is decided by about 630K people.
</p>

