<p>
  While this does give voters in Wyoming more say, it doesn’t actually give them any electoral advantage holistically speaking. In fact, the current electoral college system actually inflates the power of larger states. To understand why, let's look at the last US presidential election in 2012.
</p>

<p>
  I’m going to focus on two states with a clear blue majority & incredibly high population, NY & CA. If the electoral college works as intended, these two states shouldn’t decide the election alone.
</p>

<p>
  In 2012, NY casted close to 4,485,741 votes for Obama and CA casted about 7,854,285. Combined, that accounts for about 9% of every vote casted in 2012. However, the combined electoral college votes of NY & CA is about 16%.
</p>

<p>
  The biggest reason this number is so inflated? Every state awards electoral votes on a winner take all basis and makes the exact proportion of the popular vote irrelevant. Lets look at California as an example, which has 55 electoral votes up for grabs. In 2012 Obama won 60% of the popular vote, and got all 55 electoral votes. However, if we only gave him 60% of the electoral votes, <i>because that's proportionally how much he won in the popular vote</i>, he’d have only only won about 33 electoral votes.
</p>

