</p>

<p>
  Another huge implication of proportionally awarding electoral votes is how it could change swing states. Swing states are a few special states like Florida & Ohio where the demographics are basically 50/50 politically. Traditionally campaigns spend most of their time & money in these states, ignoring states that always go blue or red. Why bother if you know you’re going to win or lose all of the electoral votes in that state? Hence the formation of swing states, the few places in the country you can truly fight over for electoral votes.
</p>

<p>
  You’ll notice in doing this we have some major implications for our electoral map. Large states that always vote the same way like California, Texas & NY lose quite a bit of value. Several states such as a New Hampshire, Wisconsin and Mississippi automatically become purple. Except for a few outliers, most the states don’t rest too far from that purple trend line.
</p>

<p>
  In essence, politicians need something close to a 50 state strategy, and your vote suddenly becomes significantly more important even if you don’t live in a swing state.
</p>

<p>
  So, the next time someone says we need to abolish the electoral college, tell them no, we need to abolish the winner take all system.
</p>
